# UTF-8 on Windows (agent file writes)

**Dagh's machine:** Windows + PowerShell 5.1. **Known Cursor bug:** the agent **`Write` tool** often saves **UTF-16 LE** (null byte between every character). `.editorconfig` / `files.encoding` do **not** fix this — the agent write path bypasses them.

## Do

- **Edit existing files with `StrReplace`** — preserves UTF-8 on files that are already UTF-8.
- **New files or full rewrites:** use PowerShell, not `Write`:

```powershell
[System.IO.File]::WriteAllText($path, $content, (New-Object System.Text.UTF8Encoding $false))
```

- **Never** use `Out-File`, `Set-Content` (no `-Encoding`), or `>` redirection for source files — PS 5.1 defaults to UTF-16.

## Do not

- Do **not** use **`Write`** to create `.php`, `.js`, `.css`, `.md`, or `.inc.php` files, or to dump a whole file body in one call.
- Do **not** burn a session debugging CSS/PHP/layout when the real fault may be encoding — check first (below).

## Spot it (10 seconds)

- File ~**2x expected size**; hex starts with `XX 00 XX 00` (not `3C 3F 70 68` for `<?ph`).
- Cursor shows **"Binary file is not supported"** on a text file.
- PHP **dumps raw source** into the page / layout collapses after an agent edit.

## Fix it (one command, then continue the real task)

```powershell
$p = "path\to\file.ext"
$t = [System.IO.File]::ReadAllText($p, [System.Text.Encoding]::Unicode)
[System.IO.File]::WriteAllText($p, $t, (New-Object System.Text.UTF8Encoding $false))
```

If the file was never UTF-16, read as UTF-8 instead of `Unicode`. Verify: first bytes should have **no** nulls between ASCII letters.